    "body": "## Summary\n\nSplit GEMM backend-specific logic out of the shared tile op path. The common `src/op/gemm.cc` now resolves backend implementations through a registry, while CUDA, ROCm, and CPU selection/lowering details live under their own backend directories.\n\nAdd a Python GEMM implementation registry under `tilelang.backend`, with per-backend modules registering the implementation classes used by GEMM infer-layout and lowering.\n\n## Why\n\nThis keeps hardware instruction selection and backend-specific GEMM implementation choices out of the generic tile op code, matching the backend split pattern used by copy and making future backend-specific GEMM changes more localized.\n\n## Validation\n\n- `./format.sh`\n- `cmake --build build -j$(nproc)`\n- `PYTHONPATH=$(pwd) python -m compileall -q tilelang/backend tilelang/tileop/gemm`\n- CUDA GEMM smoke test, 64x64x64, max diff 0.007762908935546875\n- CPU GEMM smoke test, 64x64x64, max diff 5.7220458984375e-06\n\n\n<!-- This is an auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->\n## Summary by CodeRabbit\n\n* **New Features**\n  * Added optimized GEMM backends for CPU, CUDA, and ROCm with hardware-aware selection and multiple specialized implementations.\n\n* **Refactor**\n  * Introduced a pluggable, priority-based GEMM resolver so backends can register and be chosen at runtime.\n  * Updated Python backend and tile op dispatch to route GEMM selection through the new resolver.\n\n* **Chores**\n  * Removed legacy low-level GPU query bindings in favor of the resolver-based API.\n<!-- end of auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->",
